# RSL Mini-Hack '26 - Hackathon Ground Rules

## Context

- 90-minute time-boxed hackathon (March 25, 9:00-10:30 AM)
- Build and deploy a working web application with data storage
- Maximize AI-assisted development across ALL stages
- Deliverables: working hosted app, GitHub repo, AI workflow docs

## Official use case (March 25, 2026)

**Personal finance tracking** (full text: `docs/use-case.md`, source PDF in repo
root).

Users track **income and expenses**, organize **categories**, see **summaries**
(income, spend, balance; monthly budget/income/savings targets), use **auth**,
**responsive** UI, **database** persistence, **CRUD** on transactions, a
**landing** snapshot (month spend, % budget used, category breakdown), and a
**dashboard** with **charts**. Optional: insights, savings tips, anomalies,
natural-language Q&A.

## Repo stack (BudgetLens monorepo)

| Layer | Choice |
| ----- | ------ |
| Frontend | Next.js (in `frontend/`) |
| Backend | FastAPI (in `backend/`) |
| Database + Auth | Supabase |
| Hosting | **Vercel** for Next.js; **separate** host for FastAPI (Railway/Render/Fly recommended) |
| Remote | **GitHub** |
| UI/UX | **Google Stitch** + **Figma**; spec in **`docs/DESIGN.md`** (*Aperture Experience*) |

## Speed-First Principles

- Prefer established libraries/frameworks over custom code
- Use managed services (Supabase, Vercel, API host free tiers) over self-hosted
- Ship MVP first, polish later - working > perfect
- Avoid premature optimization; focus on core functionality
- One-command deployments **per package**; env vars documented in `.env.example`

## AI Usage Requirements (Judging Criteria)

- Use AI for brainstorming, design, coding, debugging, testing, AND deployment
- Document every AI interaction in `docs/ai-workflow.md`
- Log prompts, tool steps, screenshots, and key decisions
- Prioritize creative problem-solving over boilerplate

## Technical Constraints

- Must have user identification (login/auth)
- Must have persistent data storage (database)
- Must have CRUD operations
- Must deploy to free hosting platform(s)
- Must share source code on GitHub

## When Generating Code

- Always include error handling
- **Frontend**: TypeScript; prefer React Server Components where helpful; client fetch to FastAPI when needed
- **Backend**: Python type hints + Pydantic
- Keep components and routers small, focused, and reusable
- Use environment variables for all secrets/config
